The prepared BCND powders exhibited blue FL under UV (365 nm) irradiation and the green RTP after the UV lamp was turned off, which could be observed with the naked eye for 10 s (Fig. 1
                        ). The BCND2 was selected for the subsequent experiment because it had the optimum RTP properties (Table S1). The FL and RTP spectra of the BCND2 were further investigated. The time-resolved fluorescence spectra of BCND2 can be well fitted to double exponential function with fluorescence lifetime of 6.30 ns (Fig. 2
                        a and Table S2), but the phosphorescence decay spectra can be fitted as triple exponential function, and the phosphorescence lifetime is 1.33 s (Fig. 2b and Table S3). As shown in Fig. 2c, there are two absorption peaks at 266 and 365 nm in the solid-state UV–vis absorption spectra of BCND2, which were attributed to the π-π* transition of the aromatic group and the n-π* transition of C-N. In the liquid environment, the UV absorption spectrum has only one absorption peak at 350 nm, which is very consistent with the optimal excitation wavelength of BCND2 (Fig. 2c). In addition, BCND2 in aqueous solution showed excitation dependence under different excitation wavelengths (Fig. 2d). At the optimum excitation wavelength of 365 nm, the optimum emission peak of the FL spectroscopy and phosphorescence spectroscopy of BCND2 are 446 nm and 535 nm, respectively (Fig. S1).
